datavalue.value: Carlo Archinto of Milan (1669-1732); Adolph Sutro (1830-1898), mayor of San Francisco. A letter from George Moss (librarian of Sutro) addressed to Mrs. Morbio (presumably Mrs. Albert Morbio, Sutro's daughter), 23 May 1890, accompanies the manuscript.
Figurative details, ff. 1r-48v: One inhabited initial on gold ground; bust of a bishop on a red shield carrying the name Alexander inside a green wreath.

Other decoration, ff. 1r-48v: Border along lower edge of f. 1 of sprays of flowers decorated with gold balls; 2- and 3-line initials alternating in blue and gold with pen flourishing in red and blue respectively; headings in red centered above blocks of text.
Layout, ff. 1r-48v: 25 long lines ruled in ink.
Manuscript note: In house call number: Sutro PA 4267 P3 1464.
ff. 1r-48v: Scribal colophon, 4. 46r; back pastedown from another manuscript; written surface faces board, making writing only faintly visible.

ff. 1r-46r: ff. 44v-45v, 4 additional letters with preface to Alfonso of Naples; f. 46, letter to Francesco Pellotus of Padua; ownership note. f. 46r; ff. 46v-47v blank; 2 alphabets & excerpts from Sallust and Lucan, signed "A. B" on f. 48r; f. 48v blank.
This description provided by D. J. Dutschke and C. W. Dutschke.

Jachopo di Domenicho vinattiere de' Seghalorzi di Firenze
Inside front cover: Ex bibliotheca Com. Eq. Fabricii Orsini Rilli di Poppi. N. 263 in a Sotheby sale, ca. 1890 (according to De Ricci); Adolph Sutro (1830-1898), mayor of San Francisco.
Binding: Bound, s. XV, in half calf over squared wooden boards, wrapped with two purple ribbons, 5 brass bosses on spine with evidence of 5 others; clasp missing.
Number of scribes, ff. 1-69v: 2 breaking between ff. 17v-18.
Layout, ff. 1-69v: Gatherings of 12 leaves; 30-39 long lines frame ruled in lead.
Watermarks, ff. 1-69v: Briquet 10489 and another similar to Briquet 11659-1168.
Manuscript note: Burnt on fore edge, possibly from the 1906 fire in San Francisco that destroyed most of the Sutro Collection.
Bibliography: De Ricci, p. 26 as n. 2.

ff. 1-69v: Date and scribe's name on f. 1, in the opening rubric: "M ccc lxxxxii . . . lo scrisse Jachopo di Domenicho vinattiere de Seghalorzi di Firenze." Parchment reinforcing strips around the back of each quire.
Explicit, ff. 1-68v; f. 69r-v blank: Domene dio per sua grande possanza tutto il mondo istabilito.
This description provided by D. J. Dutschke and C. W. Dutschke.

datavalue.value: Ownership notes, mainly illegible, inside front cover, ". . . Ambroggio 1523 ad oct. A<?> ... Salus..." and " 692." De Ricci states that the volume was "last in Germany." Adolph Sutro (1830-1898), mayor of San Francisco.

ff. 1-140v: ff. 1-11, index; ff. 11v-12 non-indexed recipes in a different hand; ff. 12v-13 blank; ff. 14-16, non-indexed recipes, some in Latin; f. 16v, table of weight measurements; ff. 17-140v main text.

datavalue.value: Incipit epistola Petri Damiani de die iudicii

On f. 1, illegilbe even under ultra-violet light due to stain, "Iste liber est monachorum <?> deputatus monasterii <sancte Marie ?> <?>." On f. i verso in a modern Italian hand, "14.6.13" written over "A.42000." Adolph Sutro (1830-1898), mayor of S. F.
Binding: Bound, s. XIX with labels on spine, "Paschasii De corpore et sanguine Domini" and "Bertoni opera."
ff. 39-135: Terminus post quem provided by texts: f. 132, death note of Bonaventura Bertoni in 1719; ff. 133-134, speech by Pope Innocent in 1666 and a rhyme in Italian of an event in 1686.
ff. 1-36: On f. 1, Regis adire sacre qui vis sollemnia mense . . . (15 verses spelling "Radbertus levita"); ff. 1-2, dedicatory letter.
Explicit, ff. 1-36: Quisquis catholicorum recte dominum cuncta creasse de nichilo.
Explicit, ff. 36-38v: Dilectissimo fratri Ade Petrus peccator monachus humilis in domino salutem. Quod me, frater karissime, quid ante mundi creationem fuerit . . .

ff. 39-135: ff. 39-45v, life of St. Maurus by Maurus Verdoni; ff. 47-111v, sermons in Italian; f. 112v, list of schismatic Greeks; ff. 113-114v, Memorialein first person, signed J. Bonaventura Cesenas Capuccinus; ff. 115-132, Elucidationesagainst Calvinists.

datavalue.value: In an envelope with the manuscript, the remains of the bookplate of George John Warren Vernon (1803-1866), fifth Baron Veron; CSL accession number 22953.
Binding: Quarter bound calf, nineteenth century.

Other decoration, ff. i-iv (front and back flyleaves): 2- and 3-line initials in gold with white-patterned pink and green infilling on square white-patterned blue grounds; 1-line initials within text washed with pale yellow.
Script, ff. i-iv (front and back flyleaves): Humanistic.
Layout, ff. i-iv (front and back flyleaves): 24 long lines; ruled.
Other decoration, ff. 1r-191v: 2- and 3-line initials in red, sometimes decorated in void; paraph marks in red.
Script, ff. 1r-191v: Gothic and humanistic cursive.
Layout, ff. 1r-191v: 2 columns of 36 lines; ruled in ink.
ff. 1r-191v: The date on the last leaf, 1338, is that of the composition of the text, not of this copy.
ff. i-iv (front and back flyleaves): Continuous sequence of text from book 4 if read in the following order: f. iii r-v, ff. i r-ii v, f. iv r-v.

ff. 1r-191v: On f. 191v, column b, the resume' known as the Breviarum decretorumoften attributed to Johannes de Deo (see, for example, Jordan and Wool, Inventory of Western Manuscripts in the Biblioteca Ambrosianaregarding A 147 sup).
ff. 1r-191v: Dr. Thomas Izbicki kindly identified the text on f. 191v.
